76561198045835105,Not Recommended,269030,20269035,"Posted: 3 January, 2016",all,LordGinger,"Far too short and repetitve to recommend, even on sale."
,Recommended,269030,21060952,"Posted: 8 February, 2016",all,arcanum.zero,"This game is a great example of how there are no true quality metrics in video game design.  Graphics?  This game is entirely un-animated and the still images consist completely of low-res cartoons.  Gameplay?  You pick options off a menu.  Music?  One guitar.  Story?  You will finish it in less than a half hour.And yet The Yawhg is probably worth twice its $10 asking price.  In a market saturated with ""gameplay advancements,"" ""4K resolution,"" ""roleplaying elements,"" and hundred-hour lengths, very few game developers stop to ask themselves whether they are using these tools to do something worth doing.  The Yawhg does something worth doing and does not need any of these tools to do it.To nitpick the game's description, The Yawhg is not a ""Choose Your Own Adventure.""  Choose Your Own Adventure books very rarely had multiple main characters or stats to track.  The Yawhg is a /Gamebook,/ and while these were great fun in the 80s before we had real branching-path video games, today this is the best possible format for the medium.  The Yawhg is a perfect example of the synergy of right tools and right task, and it is worth the time of anyone who enjoys a good interactive story.  I suppose you might call this a visual novel -- I don't know, really, I feel like genre has become largely irrelevant in describing video games.The story of The Yawhg is different every time you play it, so I can't comment on its quality universally, but if you find yourself telling a story you don't care for, it will only last for 20 more minutes.  Suck it up and then start a new one.  I still recommend you finish the playthrough, however, because what comes to pass may surprise you.More like this, please, industry.  More like this."
76561198053748918,Not Recommended,269030,9294376,"Posted: 28 February, 2014",all,Hark! A raptor doth approach,"This isn't a game; it is an interactive story that has 7 pages per character, with a wrap-up using details from some of the stuff that happened in the story. You can finish a session in under 5 minutes. For the price, I would heavily recommend watching someone else play it.There is also very little gameplay to speak of. Your character accrue Attributes for each choice you make. Each location gives you a fixed Attribute boost and then a choice to expand upon it (there is usually a positive gain). At the end of the game, you will have to make a choice - the outcome of which depends on the choices you made. This means that, from a gameplay perspective, it is incredibly shallow - since every location gives you a fixed benefit at the start, simply maximising it will let you power through to ""win the game"". I, in fact, could list what locations to visit to win the game right now but that would be exceedingly heartless. But I could and that fact should display how shallow it is.Story-wise, there is some continuity from one day to another but in general, there is not much connectivity. This is to be expected between characters, the point of the story is to display days lived out in the lives of these arbitrary characters in this city. However, the fact that there is very little connectivity within the events of any individual storyline basicly renders most of the events as stand-alone vignettes that could have happened to any other character and NOT the character you chose. In other words, unless you get one of the continuity-based events (which still only really leak into the next week's event), your character does not have a developing personal storyline, just a sequence of events that happened to happen to him/her.A final point on the gameplay as it relates to the story is that you don't know the effects of your actions beforehand. So, for at least the first time you see an event, there is an element of guesswork where you have to guess whether or not the thing you intended to happen will happen. Luckily, the game's events are very simple and there isn't a lot (if any) complexity to the story. It also happens to repeat itself a lot. In fact, on my third or fourth playthrough I happened to have already seen most of the events that were offered to me.A positive point is that the game's narration between weeks is atmospheric. Another positive point is that it has very good and fitting music (in my opinion).For these reasons, I would suggest NOT BUYING THIS GAME. Instead, watch someone else play it - you will get the same experience. Watch a run-through if you think that's an exaggeration. Stay away from purchasing game. Look at it, note what it attempts to do and then move on. It is nowhere remotely worth the money (except for the music, which as I said before, is pretty good in my opinion)."
