,Recommended,269030,28997787,Posted: 3 January,all,Ticia,"Before purchasing 'The Yawhg', I had thought it to be a light-hearted, ""choose your own story"", game. Yet, what I got instead was infinitely more intriguing.The game itself offers four differentiating characters that the player can control, and in doing so will ultimately decide their own life stories. It's left up to them to improve the skills of the characters, and to make wise decisions; some of which even prove to be a bit of a catch 22.Something that I personally found to be fantastic, about The Yawhg, was that it's intended to be played from just one device. So, I can easily access play by myself, or with my friends. Whether they be online, or right next to me; which is truly brilliant. And whether or not the ""antagonist"" was defeated depended upon ALL of the players. Team work is imperative for the succession of this game.Something else that stood out to me was the violent undertones, and low-key foreshadowing of impending doom, as The Yawhg [a so-called ""storm""] approached its arrival to the town; in which the protagonists live. I'm probably running out of characters here, so I'll try to make this explanation quick. After The Yawhg has said to pass, the players are asked to select one of many professions, in an effort to re-construct the town, and whether or not they do it well depends entirely on how high their corresponding skill is. The Yawhg is just like a giant puzzle. All of the events that take place link to the game's ending, and it can be either good or bad.Will you survive The Yawhg? And even if you do, will you be happy forevermore? Take a chance, and find out."
