76561198018969815,Not Recommended,269030,15603301,"Posted: 28 April, 2015",all,acolomb1,"In two sentences: Only pick this game up at a *steep* discount, as the game is too short, and there are not enough unique scenarios to justify the price tag.  I finished four (4) complete playthroughs in under an hour and saw many repeats.More detailed review (based on the singleplayer experience):The Yawhg is not so much a choose-your-own-adventure story (there is very little narrative, and your characters are gamepieces - not people) as it is a short opportunity to build up a couple of characters' stats in a short time to fulfill the game's hidden requirements.  There are four characters from whom to choose, but the only difference among them seems to be the appearance - I didn't notice any difference in events or stats.  As a single player, the game will ask you to choose two to four characters to play, and your goal is to raise their stats (there are six stats: physique, finesse, etc.).For each turn, you will send each character to a place on the map to do a task.  There are eight locations and two possible tasks at each, so sixteen tasks in total from which to choose each turn, but two characters cannot be at the same location at the same time.  Each task will raise or lower one or more of your stats, but the only way to know what a task will affect is through trial and error.  Most tasks will also trigger a short text-based ""event,"" which may allow you to choose your character's response and further affect their stat gain/loss.  To be clear, as a fan of both visual novels and choose-your-own-adventure-type games, the game's systems are *not* the reason I am not recommending it.The problem comes from the fact that the game only consists of six weeks (each turn is a whole week).  This means that you only have six opportunities to raise each character's stats before the Yawhg appears (off-screen) and wrecks the town (again, off-screen).  At that point, you are given a choice of roles for each character to take in the rebuilding process; again, there are no explanations or listed stat requirements, so you just kind of guess.  Finally, the game checks to see if your character's stats are high enough to meet its invisible requirements, and you get a couple of epilogue slides reflecting your characters' success/failure and their fates afterwards.That's it.  Six turns, a guess, and an epilogue.  So, each playthrough is EXTREMELY short to begin with, and then there is the fact that although the game supposedly has something like 100-200 unique events (I'm not arguing that it doesn't), you will see a lot of repeats in each playthrough, so subsequent playthroughs are not as exciting.  When I first played the game, I did 3 full playthroughs: the first using 2 characters, the second using all 4, and the third using 3 just to be thorough.  All 3 playthroughs took me a combined *32 minutes*.  Thinking that maybe I missed something or was in a bad mood that day, I waited some time, then played it once more before posting this review.  Again, maybe 10 minutes, and I'm pretty sure that all but one of the events and the two ending cards were repeats.To finish, I hate to post a negative review for anything, but I just can't recommend this game at its $10 asking price given the dirth of content.  If you can get it for <$5 and plan on playing with friends, by all means go ahead: the art is unique and interesting, the music is nice, and I like the general concept -- there's simply not enough here to keep a person busy for even a single hour (and again, this is from someone who enjoys text- and menu-based games).  Sorry. :("
