,Recommended,269030,19139842,"Posted: 17 November, 2015",all,lexavian,"Quick Summary: a quick mainly text game that is best played locally with 2-4 players. I reccomend it to anyone if the price range is maybe $4-6 or if it ever adds more content.So the Yawhg is a fantasy/fairy tale game where 2-4 players play as one of 4 color themed characters. In each round of the game every player takes a turn before control passes to the next player. In each player's turn there is a particular order or structure to the turn. First the player picks a place to go and picks from one of two pre-set actions for that location. For example the player can go to the ""alchemy tower"" and ""brew potion"" or ""clean lab"".  (They are limited by only being able to choose where no one else has gone yet on that turn.) The game then rewards you a stat bonus for your action (usually +2 to one stat and +1 to another) and then generates a particular scenario based on that selection. You are given a choice during that scenario and the game will tell you how your choice went. The outcome of this choice is frequently dependent on your stats. For example, brewing potions give you +2 magic and +1 mind. After that the game says that the other wizards are thowing a cantrip party (cantrips are low-level easily-cast spells). After hearing what some other people do you can decide to do a ""simple trick"" or ""complex trick"". If you don't have high enough of a magic stat and choose ""complex trick"", you end up hurting and embarrassing yourself in the process which then causes a -2 in charm. However successfully completing the complex trick may have given you rank among your peers in the form of +2 charm. Additionally, these scenarios are interlinked and frequently someone may do something in thier turn that causes another scenario to occur in another players turn. This is seen in the demon baby excerpts from the gameplay demo above. After several round of this ""the yawhg"" arrives. Without going into too much detail, your stats and one final choice determine the outcome of the town in this trying time. The town's fate is delegated to one of 3 options, the best of which is easily obtainable. Then the game gives each player a personal ending which is dependent on the town's ending, the player's stats, thier last choice, how they spent their time, and what scenarios happened to them. For example if you get the good town ending and spent a lot of time doctoring there are at least two specific doctor endings. But if you also happened to encounter a supernatural creature at some point, then you may get an ending where you try to wrap up loose end involving that encounter.In the end, the number of outcomes and scenarios are limited and if you enjoyed the game you are left wishing there was more content to the game. (I particularly want an update or DLC). However, even after 7.5 hours on record playing this game, a new event occurred last time and a new ending. And we have yet to explore any of the towns subpar endings. This is a great game to buy on sale and then whip out to play with family or friends. It has easy intuitive menu and allows for any combination of controllers or keyboards. Players can assign both of thier characters to the same device and then pass the controller between them."
