,Recommended,269030,10836928,"Posted: 26 June, 2014",all,L.,"This is a simply-designed game - hand-drawn graphics and handwritten text. Instead of yet another game that showers you with blocks of preformatted lines, this is an adventure, two of them. This has an enchantingly human story. The player chooses the course of two lives, how they build, how they grow or how they fail. It's not another high-budget super-graphical story like any of a thousand roleplay games, instead it feels much more like a choose-your-own-adventure story. The music is heartfelt, and the storylines feel involving, despite this being a relatively short game. The closest similarity I could find is with the Stanley Parable, but that does The Yawhg a disservice - the choices for the lives of the characters really do matter and they affect what ultimately happens at the story's end. I found myself really enjoying this - it's rare for a game to have a hand-crafted heartfelt sort of feeling to it, but The Yawhg has this from beginning to end. Excellent. Rare. Interesting."
