76561198142902593,Recommended,269030,11053578,"Posted: 3 July, 2014",all,I Am Satan Lord of Darkness,Really Fun With Friends
,Recommended,269030,11055646,"Posted: 3 July, 2014",all,RohnJobert,"The term ""Visual Novel"" is usually an annoying term to read in a review. But, The Yawhg is without a doubt a visual storytelling experience that anyone who enjoys 'choose your own adventure' novels or games will love. The gameplay is minimal, you choose two to four characters (best suited for multiplayer, maybe) and choose where they will spend their single week of six. In these six weeks, the Yawhg, a mythical beast who never shows it's face to the player, will attack the town and destroy everything you've become familiar with. Because the actual weeks pass by in maybe 15 minutes, multiple playthoughs are a must. And hard to resist. You can choose to spread out your experience, attacking everything to do, or you can grind out your magic, charm, mind, and so forth at one location six weeks in a row. However, the multiple endings find a way to beat your system faster than you learned to cheat theirs. Spending time bartending for charm, you end up an alcoholic, dead from your own love. Grinding out magic at the alchemist tower leaves you alone, without love, and left to create potions to satisfy your only happiness. This is where the Yawhg becomes a ""beautiful"" experience. Albeit depressing, the levels of endings you can receive give you a feeling that you did what needed to be done. There is no need for guides, builds, playing a game the way you don't usually play just so you can have a completionist ending or a successful character stat build. This is a game that is relentless in experience that you learn on your own, and that you can only experience if you treat it like a real week by week lifestyle. This is your story to create, and it's a doozy."
,Recommended,269030,11122849,"Posted: 7 July, 2014",all,Kivivarvas,"The yawhg as a game is very much like a board game. Every day you gather stats by visiting many locations of the city, with an immense amount of different things that can happen.  After 6 weeks you choose what you want to do with those skills you`ve garnered, and depending on them, you decide the towns fate.The main meat of the game however are the immense amount of different endings. You might have angered someone you shouldn`t have during the 6 weeks. You might have decided to do something you really shouldn`t have at the end. Maybe you turn into a monster yourself! ...Or maybe you live mostly an ordinary life.The game in itself is best when played as a group. The game allows up to 4 players to go live in the town. The games biggest downfall is the fact, that it doesn`t support online multiplayer, but that is easily fixed with a call with skype as one person reads the choices out loud and does the choices for the other players like a game master.Overall, if you want a fun experience, which most likely gives you an unique ending everytime if you aren`t afraid to try something new, and you like reading, buy the game."
