,Recommended,269030,29188237,Posted: 11 January,all,a bathful of lemons,"You and your friends know *something* is coming to lay waste to your town in six weeks. You take it in turns to prepare, week by week, honing your skills so that after that *something* happens you will be able to rebuild the life you once had. Or maybe you'll just contract vampirism and die alone. Whatever works for you.I have replayed this game with many different friends and enjoyed their reactions to the unusual scenarios it threw at them, especially when seemingly minor decisions come back to haunt them. It's a very short game but lasts just as long as it needs to. Soundtrack and visual style work perfectly. Only criticism is the lack of online multiplayer."
76561198106211380,Recommended,269030,28531147,"Posted: 22 December, 2016",all,Gpupdate /force,"If you're looking for a game you'll play three maybe four times for a total of 2 hours. Then this is the game for you.The Yawgh consists of a number of turns where you decide which part of town you go to, and then decide how you will approache that event and then resolve it before the""Yawgh"" happens. It's somewhat a graceful throwback to text based games which too much effort thrown into the ""feel"" of the game, rather than focus on making the events more vast and random, often after playthrough number three you will see many of the same ""Haunting"" events that disinterested you in the first couple of playthrough's. It is somewhat interesting to where your character ends up at the end of the game, but not interesting enough to make you want to play it a fifth time.The Yawgh is perfect for a group of four friends with nothing better to do than to play a random game or watch Space Jam."
